## CODE STANDARDS

### TypeScript
- Strict mode always on
- No `any` types — ever
- All API responses typed with Zod schemas
- All database queries go through typed repository layer
- Errors are typed, never thrown raw

### File Structure
```
sentinel/
  /app                  → Next.js App Router pages
  /app/api              → API routes (REST)
  /components           → Shared UI components
  /components/sentinel  → Sentinel-specific components
  /lib                  → Utilities, helpers, constants
  /lib/crypto           → Hashing, signing, verification logic
  /lib/db               → Database client, repositories
  /lib/reports          → Report generation (Stage 3)
  /lib/validation       → Zod schemas
  /types                → Shared TypeScript types
  /docs                 → Living documentation (markdown)
  /tests                → Unit + integration tests
  .cursorrules          → This file
  schema.sql            → PostgreSQL-compatible schema reference

blackhorse/             ← sibling directory (Protocol repo) — all 7 stages built
  /core                 → Stage 1: BitStream, RingBuffer, utils
  /language             → Stage 2: BHL encoder/decoder/packet
  /compression          → Stage 3: LZ77 compressor
  /crypto/symmetric     → Stage 4: ChaCha20
  /crypto/asymmetric    → Stage 5: Curve25519 + HKDF
  /crypto/signing       → Stage 6: HMAC-SHA256 + BHL signing
  /interface            → Stage 7: BlackhorseSession (full pipeline)
  /docs                 → BHL_SPEC.md, AI_CONTEXT.md
  /tests                → 144 passing tests
```

### Component Rules
- Every component has a JSDoc comment explaining its purpose
- Props interfaces are always explicit, never inferred
- No inline styles — Tailwind only
- No magic numbers — use named constants from lib/constants.ts
- Server components by default; client components only when necessary ("use client")

### API Rules
- All endpoints validate input with Zod
- All endpoints return: `{ success: true, data: T }` or `{ success: false, error: string }`
- Rate limiting on all public endpoints (TODO Stage 4)
- Auth required on all write endpoints (TODO Stage 4)
- Idempotency keys on artifact ingestion (TODO Stage 2)

### Crypto Rules
- All hashing is server-side — never trust client-computed hashes
- Timestamps are server-assigned — never trust client-provided timestamps
- Every artifact gets: SHA-256 hash, SHA-3-512 hash, ISO 8601 timestamp, server nonce
- SHA-3-512 is the quantum-transition hash — feeds into BHL encoding at Stage 6
- Hash verification is deterministic and auditable
- For future post-quantum decisions: defer to ../blackhorse/docs/BHL_SPEC.md

---

## DATABASE SCHEMA (Reference)

Full schema in schema.sql. Key tables:

  artifacts       (id, hash_sha256, hash_sha3_512, timestamp_iso, source_type,
                   size_bytes, mime_type, file_name, content, source_url,
                   metadata_json, nonce, status, created_at)

  verifications   (id, artifact_id, assertion_text, status, evidence_json,
                   verified_at, verifier_id, created_at)

  reports         (id, title, version, artifacts_json, verifications_json,
                   integrity_hash, created_at, exported_at)

  bhl_records     (id, artifact_id, bhl_encoded_hash, protocol_version,
                   dilithium_signature, signed_at, created_at)

  organizations   (id, name, tier, settings_json, created_at)  [Stage 4+]
  api_keys        (id, org_id, key_hash, permissions_json, ...)  [Stage 4+]
  audit_logs      (id, org_id, action, resource_id, ...)  [Stage 4+]

